How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at that time sold in most cases trips only to the socialist bloc, as trips to the West were very restricted.
Czech tourists were therefore on vacation on the beaches of the RDA (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one could travel to Yugoslavia, however, then the Yugoslav regime declined west and the journeys of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e., also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually not even by the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, if not, the individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West in those times, but one was supposed to put on the tail with a sleeping bag and spend all night, or have "well known" in the agency.
Even so, he wasn't all won.
The so-called "promise of change" that was the condition for trips to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable agent", which thus could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of the Czechs spent their vacation in their own country, so there were a large number of cabins and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired. This custom still persists.
The way of travelling the Czechs has suffered a genuine revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was not going to spend vacations in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, which we are no longer aware of today, the fact that the current favorite destination, Croatia, until 1989 could not travel freely, because it was part of the Yugoslavia then.
In the early 1990s, visas were imposed to travel to Western European neighbouring States, resulting in an enormous wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not see the crowds from the excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris the Czech groups in the parks were sleeping in tents, since our incomes at the time did not allow us to pay a hotel or a pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs of that time was to take with them food (preserved, stuffed, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, buy free Western currency.
Our standard of living increased, and with it also average wages, which about 1997 resulted in an increase in travel demand.
With the increase in travel demand, since 1997 the agencies regularly began preparing travel using charter flight connections, which brought the price of travel down dramatically compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for the volume of passengers.
By the end of the 90th century, Czechs were already travelling visa-free to almost all developed countries, except the United States, which further simplified our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutional tourism happened in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from Czechia to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists have been starting from faraway and hot countries. This winter will fly directly from Chechnya to 12 exotic destinations.
The exotic countries are currently visiting nearly 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this era, which symbolizes our post-revolutional development, came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the United States eliminated visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, have spent on travel abroad more than 15,000 Czech crowns per head, including expenses on the stay site.
