On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to having committed a massacre in Norway in July, who left 77 dead, faced his first public court hearing.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from being alone in cyberspace: He had spent most of his time before his attack against his computer, talking to some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social networks.
After the tragedy of this summer, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - you just have to get on Facebook.
"We realized that it was not so hard to reach them," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a report recently published on European digital populism by the British Research Centre DEMOS.
Facebook's personal information range is so encyclopedic, says Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine their desired demographic characteristics with scientific accuracy - the way sellers have been using for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then they gave them advertisements, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to complete a survey asking about their educational level, attitudes to violence and optimism about their own future.
On arriving through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 followers of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - all without leaving the office.
"It's a totally new way to do an investigation," says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not entirely surprising: The online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, men and angry about immigration.
However, in a sort of turn, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind the computer screen."
DEMOS' work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new and important tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centres, medical researchers and political scientists are using the site to study everything, from health problems to social trends as expressed in the "I like", messages on the walls and state updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content per day, Facebook's "data supernova" is generating an increase in research, boosting the number of academic jobs with the name of the site on the title up to nearly 800% in the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study the people you could not approach with a folder on the street.
"Before, when you were trying to survey people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You should go through the party, and they would never allow you access," says Bartlett.
"Facebook eliminates all that--you go to them directly."
Others say that the site could provide a way to identify and address social-health problems.
A recent study carried out by Dr. Megan Moreno, University of Wisconsin-Madison and her colleagues found that university students who spoke about her rubber exploits on Facebook had a significantly greater risk of having drinking problems than students who remained silent on the subject.
Moreno suggests that students’ peers, such as residential counselors, could control the site and intervene to help a student who publishes too many state updates with their drunks.
"You can't deal with a problem if you can't diagnose it," said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Child Research Institute, Washington Post said.
"We found a way to identify children at risk who would otherwise not be diagnosed."
Facebook is also constantly "pinking" its own population for data.
The Site Data Team has developed statistics on the state of the relationship and Valentine's Day, the expectation of electoral participation in the middle of the 2010 legislative period, and an index of National Happiness (mainly using the information that can be accessed - digital freedom defenders for a long time ago claim that the site should make available to others their large amount of data for research).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them, likes them or not - the sacrifice for being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is allowing the site to undermine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey they don't even know?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect their off-line data, online is a free bar for everyone.
