Legends about traps are widely spread in school and university exams.
There have been cases in which teachers have given the responses of the exams to students in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching the contrary are sending the message that lying and deception are acceptable.
How deceptive are we?
On any day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere 10 to 200 times.
That's for sure, many of those lies are pious lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of getting to know each other.
Detecting lies, or "the location of lies", is an essential skill that we must acquire all, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a table game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: "I have you", the detection of deception is a branch of serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained over the past six decades in prestigious universities that carried out research projects in depth, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the investigation is that the old myths about lies have been refuted.
Liars do look in the eyes.
Not always tartmudean, bluffing, rubbed or restless.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are hard to detect or expose.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, the formation of questions and times.
I spent several years investigating scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and always emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that the detection of deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate through our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, or negotiating management.
Good liars have the ability to read others well, making them feel at ease, managing their own emotions and knowingly how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more "self-oriented minds", while women say more "oriented towards others" lies -- usually to protect the feelings of someone -- that married people less often lie to their couples than those who are not married (but the lies they usually say are "enormous").
We also know that if you are perceived as a wrongdoer, others will feel less guilty when you lie to him.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First, observe the subject's usual behavior.
This is called "create a baseline."
Helps provide reference points to measure later changes.
Watch the subject's posture, laughter and vocal characteristic.
I'd better know if someone usually hit his foot all the time to avoid making unfair accusations when he sees his feet banging in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for misleading, verbal and nonverbal behaviour groups.
Consider these behavior groups as alarm signals, not as proof of deception.
People who cheat can freeze the upper part of the body by trying to remember their history, can point their feet towards the door, lean towards a exit, change their posture significantly or exhibit a "post-interview mishaps" -- that exaggerated breath of relief and posture change once all the difficult questions have ended.
The interviewers often falsely show that the interview has ended just to seek that post-interview relief.
He also pays attention to the subject's vocabulary.
Scott Peterson kicked his ass to the bottom and used the past time as he claimed that his murdered wife was alive, launching a search for her at the national level.
People who cheat can also use a distant language: "I didn't have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when you answer a difficult question: "Well... to tell you the truth... until I... understand."
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning sign.
There is no magic formula to detect lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone to avoid being victimized by the scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
