Any blocking or delay in their efforts could result in a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks joined the pressure by warning that a failure in Monti would be a disaster.
Monti started consultations with political parties, trade unions and business groups on Monday, as well as youth and women's organizations.
It will end your round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief breath at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of Italian debt have now returned to critical levels between uncertainty as to whether the new prime minister would succeed.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of 1.8 billion euros, would be too much for the current financial defences of the eurozone.
