MSS announces protocol to find gene obesity
Leads Social Security an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people; is supported by IGN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it conducts an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people, called the 'Genetics of obesity in children and adolescents' protocol, which will enable markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital de Specialidades of the Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by graduate specialists and students of the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvesav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (INP).
In the investigation, the population is invited to participate whether or not they are entitled to participate in the sport units participating in the IMSS in the Mexico Valley, where the tests are carried out for minors, every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the sports unit Cuauhtémoc (State of Mexico West) and that since 8 October, the activity is carried out in the sports unit Nezahualcoyolt (State of Mexico East).
Once the objective of meeting 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Independence Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and the importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify in Mexican children and young people risk factors to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
At the celebration of World Diabetes Day on 14 November, it stated that the objective is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about the physical activity and a history of hereditary diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger suffering such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturdays all participants are applied anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetic levels (it is sought to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López pointed out that this research is due to the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys noted that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of children, of 77 percent in obesity, and girls of 47 percent; in terms of overweight, a dramatic rise was also observed,' noted the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from others by their genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent American Indian heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African, and this condition is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, obesity genetics translates into the inability to burn the excess of energy that we consume (calories) and is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the comprehensive assessment of children, which allows them to detect if they present any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (cantonosis) on the neck and forearm, indicating the probability of metabolic and even predisabetes alterations.
The information is handled in a confidential manner, the doctors deliver it in writing to the parents, who are explained to each of the measurements and changes in the lifestyle that must be carried out to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic sufferings: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of the television and use means of transport instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to high caloric intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugared beverages, carbohydrates (tamals, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetics that are analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would prevent berries
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Chemical Faculty, develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs sent by the floor were met, it would not be necessary to repair about 200,000 berries every rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphalt floor is the right one, the berries could be reduced in quantity or even completely eliminated.
At his conference A technological opinion of the berries, dictated within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, revealed that the laboratory in charge develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Najera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and hence the formation of berries.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphalts, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the floor its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists of that at high temperatures, close to 180 degrees, behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees centigrade its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees centigrade has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes broken, added.
The above means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but is being modified during the day according to the environmental and temperature conditions, the chemical engineering specialist warned.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible flooring, which consists of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that constitutes the folder, pointed, is bathed with asphalt.
By transiting the vehicles and generating efforts, it allows the forces to spread very well on the floor.
If it were to be modified asphalt, they would be even better spread, said the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt folder, abounded, a last layer is placed, called the tread folder, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, an sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
