This was the work of the caleño that identified Alfonso Cano's body
A lophoscopist from Cali went to history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is key.
On November 4th, a trophopist of Cali's ITC went to history as the man who confirmed the identity of the chief of the Farcs: "Alfonso Cano", through his fingerprints.
Of the seven loposcopes working in the ITC section, that week was the turn of "availability" to Eliasar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the judicial investigation area for 21 years.
At the start of his career, González worked in municipalities of the Chocó, where he often had to stay in the jungle for more than five days to reach the site where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of the Valley and, after taking the corresponding courses, he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the study of friction skin, that is, palms of the hands and feet.
The week of the operation against Alfonso Cano alias to Elias warned him to wear minimum clothes for three days.
Something big was waiting for you.
Friday night he left for the Caucasus on a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected of being the man who was leading the world's oldest guerrilla, so he was asked to carry the decactillary card of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the research team at the site where the body was found, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, as it was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He was beardless, dressed like a peasant in the area, without glasses and much thinner.
But the prints don't lie.
accompanied by a galtonian lens, ink, a transplanter and a flashlight, Eliasar compared the fingerprints of the body with those of the card.
His eye didn't fail: it was Alfonso Cano.
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was responsible for confirming the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, who was the chief of the Farcs.
In search of the footprint
For a dictator of the Sijín in Cali, the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made to Eliasar González, in the press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
Many people don't know our work.
Dactyloscopic is an accurate science, without margin of error, that can become a key in the resolution of crimes.
Apart from the identification of corpses, lophoscopists support investigations for crimes such as theft and murder and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When captured, many delinquents have false ballots or have no papers.
We take fingerprints and search them in the database.
The investigator reported that, in a case of theft, he was touched to remove a piece of wall from a house, for in that place the thief had supported his hand to pull out a strong box full of jewels and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not suitable surfaces to get a fingerprint, but in that case we were able to get the fingerprint of the whole hand and identify the criminal, who had participated in different thefts," he recalled.
The fingerprints may also rule out or reaffirm suspects in cases of murder.
Recently they found a dead man, with liquor bottles around him.
Through the investigation, it was determined that a family member could be a suspect of the crime and, indeed, a trace in the bottle coincided.
Although this does not guarantee that he was the killer, it does place him at the scene of the crime.
An ITC ectioscopicist explained that in the objects "the traces are taken out with chemical or physical reagents".
When they appear, a transplant or tape is used to lift them.
After this, the prints are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or the Register.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians," said ITC expert.
He made it clear that not everything is as shown in the CSI television program.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, not everything that is touched becomes a mark.
However, if it can be used, if the respective quota is made.
