Introduction of a budgetary "gold rule" in the Constitution
The Government of the Great Christian Social Coalition, which is in power in Austria, has decided on Tuesday to include in the Constitution a budgetary "gold rule" to reduce the public deficit and thus prevent a possible degradation of the sovereign note of Austria by credit rating agencies (triple A).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor himself, Werner Faymann, who announced this decision after a Council of Ministers, when the Austrian public debt reached 74.6%, a much higher than the maximum limit of 60% set by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly lower than the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's solvency was reduced to a single level, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay EUR 3. billion more in interest every year," said Christian Christian Democrat Vice-Chanceller, Michael Spindelegger.
Austria thus responded to a request from the Brussels Summit to the euro area member countries of October 26, in which the Heads of State and Government called for the inclusion, by the end of 2012, of the reduction of the public deficit and the recovery of the balance of public accounts in the Constitution or an equivalent law.
The device adopted by the Austrian Government approaches the "German model", since Germany was the first European country to adopt that type of "rule".
Before 2017, the structural public deficit should decrease by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year, and, as of 2017, the federal government's structural deficit should not exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while the regional States, as well as the communes, should present balanced budgets.
The objective is to reduce public debt by 60 per cent by 2020/2021 under the Maastricht Treaty.
