The North Stream, a new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream pipeline, which directly communicates Western Europe with Russia through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, has wanted to celebrate the event with great pump.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the shores of the Baltic, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, at the inauguration of the North Stream, the new pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart, Mark Rutte, have turned together the steering wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 million cubic metres of Russian gas will reach Western Europe each year through a first 1,224 km to communicate the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube should be completed at the end of 2012 which will provide a total of 55,000 million cubic metres of gas, that is, enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, the possibility of building a third tube by the same route is already discussed.
For Gazprom, the completion in time of this enormous work presents air of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the North Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding land-use by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
All of a sudden, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be harder to influence Russia by threatening it by closing its access to the markets in Western Europe.
At the high point of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the North Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the matter is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of Europe of energy, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has known, in just five years, to triumph over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
"This pipeline is a component of our association with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically," said François Fillon during the gas pipeline opening, demonstrating to what extent the major gas sector contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles on the faces of the Gazprom directors, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The underwater tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it against the anchorages of the ships.
It is supported at the bottom of the sea, an average of 200 m deep.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid mines that date back to World War II.
"It was necessary to withdraw or destroy a hundred of them, by caution," says Jens Müller, spokesman for North Stream society.
The protection measures for fauna and flora were also extremely necessary.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs as 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted throughout its length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in the waters of Sweden, but the project's leaders gave up on seeing that the Swedes were not prepared to allow a Russian state society to be established permanently in the sea off their shores.
"If it happens, we'll interrupt the gas in less than a minute," needs Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas of the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the manufacturers do not think that there is any chance of a leak, since they have planned joints which, according to the forecasts, will run every 100,000 years.
Control of the state of the pipeline is guaranteed by a underwater robot carried out by a vessel, carrying out external inspections, as well as by a device circulating through the interior of the pipeline.
With the form of a pure, it is inserted into the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for 50 years without need of any repair.
The gas circulation is simply guaranteed by pressure.
At first it is 200 bar and, at the exit of 100 bar.
Five companies have united their forces to be able to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
It was joined by the Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and exploiting the pipeline.
It has its seat in Zoug, Switzerland, where the tax is especially favourable.
After that, Gazprom rented to that company, for a period of twenty-five years renewable, all the gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will pay you for total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is actually being transported," says Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline has been brought to an end by 30% with the contribution of the shareholders and by 70% with bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach EUR 7.400 million for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure they will not go beyond their investment, as Gazprom alone takes the risk of spending.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pines.
Some valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet door.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas upon arrival before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives a million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a brand name card.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people the taste for writing.
It has an adventure air, hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine calendar is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aged by the time.
However, the Moleskine Calendars with the present aspect were born... in 1997.
The Italian Modo Mode company, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch a notebook of design notes, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then the company consultant, was responsible for the launch of the new product.
The calendar is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin (top leather), which refers to a varnished cotton used, among other things, to cover the banquets.
This type of notebook was greatly appreciated by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted to the current taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who since then became responsible for the brand in Mode Mode.
And he succeeded.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26 per cent, up to a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
Far has remained the confidential production of the first few years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer's profile, as the notebook attracts both business men and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, their users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cult.
The small Italian company, which had twelve workers at its beginnings, now owns about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
It distributes its notebooks in bookstores, from Fnac to the small shops in the center of cities, and has been able to impose its identity.
"We have adapted to times and the need to write, despite the rise of e-mails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists expose their own notebook.
In August, he also launched a notebook with leopard tapas, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Enjoying its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agendas, pens, computer fonds... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that provokes envy: in autumn 2006, Mode was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, currently Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of the disabled are looking for a job.
The XV Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a resolved public policy, applied since 2005, the unemployment rate among the disabled doubles the average rate: 19%, compared to 9% for the population as a whole.
Discouragement?
"No," says Éric Blanchet, director general of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made over the past 15 years has been considerable.
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice as high as the average.
"But there's still a lot to do."
It is worth mentioning that the disabled continue to face numerous obstacles to access to employment.
They tend to be older: 37% are over 50 years old (17% average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80 per cent have not finished their bachelor's degree, and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
In other words, there are many issues that make it especially difficult to return to work and that "constitute the question of the problem," says Christian Grapin, director general of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
Moreover, there are those who are not mentioned; people's mentality advances, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Enterprise association for the Cité noted that the directors surveyed have "a low level of knowledge about disabilities", with an "excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physical or intellectual disabilities".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% disabled workers, which was set in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest figures available in 2008, they have reached a ratio of 2.6 per cent.
"Now we reach about 3%," said Pierre Blanc, director general of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting the contributions of companies that do not respect this law.
The proof: the number of establishment "subject to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, has decreased from 2007 to 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act, which increased contributions, has generated great pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects true awareness, particularly among the large groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of companies with between 20 and 49 employees have disabled employees on their staff, compared with 82 per cent of enterprises between 100 and 199 workers.
